The Subcompact Alpha is the perfect choice for concealed carry, or professional duty use, with an overall weight just under 25oz and an overall height and width at 4.9” and 1.2” respectively.  Though the SDP Subcompact Alpha is small in stature it does not sacrifice in quality or performance.Through precision machining and hand fitting by a master gunsmith, the SDP Subcompact Alpha can achieve similar groupings to that of its larger counterpart, the Compact Alpha.The Subcompact Alpha shares more than just high performance figures with the larger pistols in the Alpha line.It also features a steel slide machined from billet.The upper frame, machined from billet aluminum, features full length internal guide rails which provide very smooth slide operation as well as solid barrel lock up.The pistol grip is polymer and textured for maximum ergonomics and grip.The pistol grip is also contoured to offer high hand placement to compliment the low bore axis, which assist the shooter with managing recoil.  Ambidextrous features include the decocking lever and a magazine release that can be switched to either side.The slide release lever also serves as the take-down pin and is located on the left side of the Subcompact Alpha.The white dot front sight is easy to see in contrast to the black rear sight.The competition inspired trigger is very smooth, in both double and single action mode, with a clean break and short, crisp, reset.Every component of the SDP Subcompact is manufactured to the highest standards and tolerances are extremely tight.Defined by precision, the Subcompact Alpha is the only choice for discerning shooters that demand the utmost in build quality and performance.

postcontent:
For sale or trade is a unique Mossberg 5500 semiauto shotgun decked out for the zombie apocalype.  This shotgun features a shortened barrel with a Tromix Shark muzzle-brake permanently installed, a Choate magazine extension (8 rounds capacity) and a buttstock that has been shortened into a "bird's head" configuration.  The 5500 has a short recoil system that didn't go far back into the buttstock, so the action itself is completely unmodified, and the top-mounted safety is more ergonomic for this grip than button-type safeties are.  This gun shoots great from the hip or from eye level (I've shot in one-handed but wouldn't recommend it to the weak of heart or wrist).  

I took on this project for fun but it would be an effective home defense or breaching shotgun, and it certainly will be the only one of its kind on the block.  More pics available on request.  I would be willing to ship to an out of state FFL if required.

postcontent: I like many other's are glad to finally see that .22 ammo is back on the shelf at a regular basis, Dick's, Gander Mtn, Field & Stream, Cabella's, Bass Pro shop, all seem to have .22 ammo in stock 24/7 All of the Dick's in Raleigh and Cary have the Winchester 555 boxes in stock just about every day lately, along with many others like Federal auto match in the 325 round box, CCI Swamp People 300 round boxes, CCI Mini-Mag 100 round boxes, CCI Stingers, Winchester 222, 333, and 1000 round boxes, you can find just about what ever you want, a lot different from a year or two ago, One thing that I have noticed is the jump in prices lately, before all of this madness you could get a 525 Round box of Remington Golden Bullet's for about $12.95   then when the ammo started to slowly make a comeback about 6 months ago, Field & Stream in Cary had a ton of it for $24.95...(A 100% Increase)... about two months ago the same ammo went up to $29.95.. I was in Dick's last Friday and grabbed a box of it, I got to the register and the manager said it went up to $34.95+ tax that comes to $37.57 the manager informed me that it was going up again around the end of July, Im telling you that the Manufacturer's have us by the BALL'S, they know exactly whats going on, they know that they can just about name there price and you will have to pay it if you want to shoot your .22  The manufacturer's are just as bad as the Sorry Ass Gouger's on Armslist, next thing you know it will be over .15 a round... A lot different from when my Grandfather bought me my first Ruger 10/22 in 1964, a box of Winchester Wildcat's was .50 cents... Every one should just stop buying the overpriced crap for a while and send the manufacturers a message, If everyone stops buying it for a while they will drop the prices back down to reality, the pricing has gotten way out of hand and there is no one to blame but the manufacturer's not the Consumer's

The AK Adaptive Rail System—AKARS™—is a weapon upgrade that replaces the rear sight leaf and the receiver’s top cover on the Kalashnikov assault rifle, 1947 & 1974 models (AK-47/74) and its variants. While retaining the durability and ruggedness of the AK models, the AKARS™ upgrade allows effective neutralization for many of the AK weapon system's traditional limitations and brings it in direct competition with long recognized weapon systems known for better accuracy—such as the original AR- 10/15 design and its variants, the M16 / M4 models.
Like the AK variants, the installed AKARS™ mounting system works in any environment from casual and competitive to battlefield condition.
